{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486676"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:41:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:41:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"157"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/157"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.55,0.01,0.02,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77525"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/157"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63037"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"214"},{"type":"tags","id":"631"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26494"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44612"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77525"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-week history of a painless swelling in the right side of his scrotum. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The left side of the scrotum and its contents are normal. On the right side, there is a soft 6 cm swelling and the testis can be felt clearly within the swelling. The spermatic cord can be felt as a distinct entity. The swelling trans-illuminates.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassure and review in one month","Scrotal ultrasound","Urinary microscopy and culture","Fine needle aspiration cytology","Testicular tumour marker studies"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of a right-sided hydrocele, which is a collection of fluid within the tunica vaginalis of the scrotum. While hydroceles are often benign, any potential sinister underlying cause must be considered. Whilst testicular cancer is not common, it often presents in the way described in this scenario. Most often the condition is seen in young men of age range 20 -34. Whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance and review\u003C/strong\u003E might be quite appropriate for an older man, in this case a more active approach would be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScrotal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation as it can confirm the presence of a hydrocele while simultaneously evaluating the underlying testicular tissue for masses or other pathology. It is non-invasive, readily available, and provides excellent visualisation of scrotal contents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETesticular tumour marker studies\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated if ultrasound reveals a suspicious lesion, but should not be the first investigation as they cannot localise or characterise the swelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration cytology\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated as the initial investigation because if the swelling represents a testicular tumour, the procedure could cause tumour seeding along the needle tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were symptoms suggesting infection such as pain, fever, or urinary symptoms, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in managing scrotal swellings is to exclude malignancy before considering more invasive diagnostic or therapeutic procedures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ultrasound is the first-line investigation for scrotal swellings to differentiate between hydrocele and other pathology.","Fine needle aspiration is contraindicated in scrotal swellings until malignancy has been excluded."],"references":["Crawford P, Crop JA. Evaluation of scrotal masses. Am Fam Physician. 2014;89(9):723-7. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2014/0501/p723.html/1000","Hoang VT, Van HAT, Hoang TH, et al. A Review of Classification, Diagnosis, and Management of Hydrocele. J Ultrasound Med 2024;43:599\u2013607. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38010662/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63037"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"157"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63037"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T11:59:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T11:59:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"157"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77525"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":nu